<subsection xml:id="subsec-properties-of-rotation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Properties of Rotation</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the properties of rotation in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define rotation as a transformation that turns an object through an angle about a fixed point (centre of rotation). Identify the centre, angle, and direction (clockwise/anticlockwise) of rotation. State the key properties: distances from centre are preserved, angle of rotation is constant for all points, and shape and size are preserved.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify the centre and angle of rotation given an object and its image. Determine the properties of rotation by examining object-image pairs. Apply rotation rules (<m>90°</m>, <m>180°</m>, <m>270°</m>) on the Cartesian plane.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply properties of rotation to solve geometric problems. Recognise rotation in real-world contexts (clock hands, wheels, doors). Use rotation to create symmetric patterns.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/properties-of-rotation.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/step-by-step-guide_properties-of-rotation.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Exploring Properties of Rotation</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p>
                    Graph paper, ruler, protractor, pencil
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, asking probing questions: <q>What stays the same?</q>, <q>What changes?</q>, <q>What about <m>180°</m>?</q>, <q>Different centre?</q> Expected answers: distances preserved, shape preserved, angle same for all points, only position changes.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Interactive Exploration</title>
                <p>
                    If you have an Internet connection, show Learners <xref ref="exploration-rotate-prop"/>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

         <activity xml:id="auto_vssxe3xn">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_kbgshok4">
                <p xml:id="auto_3g8fafy2">
                    <alert>Work in pairs</alert>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_q7vj0d0e">
                     <m>\textbf{What you need:}</m> Graph paper, a ruler, a protractor and a pencil.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="auto_rddma22m">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j1ur6ts0">
                       On a graph paper, draw triangle <m>ABC</m> and its image, triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> as shown in the figure below.
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_3qfewuan">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j7em4rmt">
                        Pick a point on the graph to act as the centre of rotation. Mark this point <m>O</m>
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties1.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_hnarmom1">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hh3p9pyy">
                        Using a ruler, draw a straight line from point <m>A</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>A'</m> to <m>O</m> as shown below. 
                        Measure the distance <m>OA</m> and <m>OA'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties2.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_2pef5pm9">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1ik3cn8v">
                        Similarly, draw a straight line from point <m>B</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>B'</m> to <m>O</m>. Measure the distance <m>OB</m> and <m>OB'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties3.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_3pncczrj">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_irzs32qg">
                        Finally, draw a straight line from point <m>C</m> to <m>O</m> and also from point <m>C'</m> to <m>O</m>. Measure the distance <m>OC</m> and <m>OC'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                    <image source="rotation-properties4.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_ls02yv5f">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_efp9rzmy">
                        Now using a protractor, measure <m>\angle\, AOA'</m>, <m>\angle\, BOB'</m> and <m>\angle\, COC'</m> and record your results. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
         </activity>
        <exploration xml:id="exploration-rotate-prop">
         <figure xml:id="fig-activity-properties-rotation">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Measuring Properties of Rotation</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-properties-rotation-act" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/properties-of-rotation-activity.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-properties-rotation-act" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-properties-rotation-act">
                    <p>
                        Follow the steps of your activity using this interactive board! Adjust the angle slider or drag the center of rotation <m>O</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Use the checkboxes at the bottom left to systematically draw the lines from the vertices to the center <m>O</m>. Observe the text calculations at the bottom right to verify that the distance from the object to the center is exactly equal to the distance from the image to the center.
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the key properties and rotation rules.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

        <insight>
            <p xml:id="auto_nn6tdadb">
                The distance <m>AO=A'O</m>, <m>BO=B'O</m> and <m>CO=C'O</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_27olt4p1">
                The distance from a point to the centre of rotation is the same as the distance from the image of that point to the centre of rotation.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_zz69scg3">
                <m>\angle\, AOA'=</m> <m>\angle\, BOB'=</m>  <m>\angle\, COC'=90^\circ</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_f46cyj6d">
                The angle of rotation is the same for all points in the shape.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_2rqq4ln6">
                In this case, Point <m>O</m> is the centre of rotation and angle <m>90^\circ</m> is the angle of rotation.
            </p>
        
            <p xml:id="auto_fgoo066d">
                <m>\textbf{Note:}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_hernk1gc">
                <ul xml:id="auto_v1m84dko">
                    <li xml:id="auto_z2qtipwa">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6tizep1b">
                            A rotation in the anticlockwise direction is taken to be positive  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> anticlockwise is <m>+45^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_fakwyobg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3bwwkixe">
                            A rotation in the clockwise direction is taken to be negative  i.e a rotation of <m>45^\circ</m> clockwise is <m>-45^\circ</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_2x6j43qe">
                        <p xml:id="auto_j1lbr28e">
                            In general, for a rotation to be completely defined, the centre and angle of rotation must be stated.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
             <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Properties</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Centre stays fixed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Distance from centre preserved (<m>OA = OA'</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Angle of rotation same for all points.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Shape and size preserved (congruent).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Orientation preserved (unlike reflection).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Rotation Rules</title>
            <table>
                <title>Rotation Rules about the Origin</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Rotation</cell>
                        <cell>Rule</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>90°</m> anticlockwise</cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-y, x)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>180°</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (-x, -y)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>270°</m> anticlockwise / <m>90°</m> clockwise</cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (y, -x)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>360°</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(x,y) \to (x, y)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Finding the Centre of Rotation</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Perpendicular Bisector Method:</alert> Draw segment <m>PP'</m>, draw its perpendicular bisector, repeat for <m>QQ'</m>, the intersection is the centre of rotation.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Misconception Alert:</alert> <q>Rotation about the ORIGIN is simpler. Rotation about other centres requires translation first.</q>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
        </insight>

            <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply rotation rules and verify properties.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through worked examples. Emphasize verifying distances from the centre are preserved. Use tables to organise coordinate calculations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

